s with respect and accord them constitutional recognition. As this book demonstrates, the Nuu-chah-nulth principles of recognition, consent, and continuity, embodied in songs, language, and ceremonies, hold the promise of achieving sustainable lifeways in this shared struggle for balance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482128540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774821285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774821285/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles